<paragraph id="8B810A64FF9D4610FF32FA01FC3AFE23" blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1338]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">
<emphasis id="B94AD676FF9D4610FF32FA01FEB8FEBD" bold="true" box="[199,371,257,282]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">
Notes on 
<typeStatus id="5485B4C6FF9D4610FEC0FA01FEB8FEBD" box="[309,371,257,282]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">types</typeStatus>
</emphasis>
. The “small supra-antennal spot” on the frons in the original description in Melander (
<number id="3DF61843FF9D4610FACAFA01FAB2FEBD" box="[1343,1401,257,282]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" value="1950.0">1950</number>
) is not a pigmented mark but a grease mark. The frons is completely yellow in the 
<typeStatus id="5485B4C6FF9D4610FBD0FA24FB40FE9A" box="[1061,1163,292,317]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">holotype</typeStatus>
. The 
<typeStatus id="5485B4C6FF9D4610FB3FFA24FAE7FE9A" box="[1226,1324,292,317]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">holotype</typeStatus>
female is greasy on the wings and head, otherwise is in fair condition. There is a small tear at the base of the left wing and the right antennal segments beyond the pedicel have broken off and are missing.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32459EFFF9D4610FF32FA8EFEDAFC33" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B810A64FF9D4610FF32FA8EFAE1FDF0" blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1338]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">
<emphasis id="B94AD676FF9D4610FF32FA8EFE64FE00" bold="true" box="[199,431,398,423]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">Diagnostic features</emphasis>
. Face and frons yellow; postgena without posterior extension (
<figureCitation id="130516E1FF9D4610FB78FA8EFB1BFE00" box="[1165,1232,398,423]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,249,1989,2011]" captionTargetBox="[156,1430,768,1958]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,758,1965]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Platypygus americanus holotype: a — lateral view, b — wing, c — dorsal view of mesonotum and abdomen." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248550/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">
Fig. 
<number id="3DF61843FF9D4610FB30FA8FFB1BFE00" box="[1221,1232,399,423]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
a); occiput black; pronotum with small orange mark dorsomedially; mesonotum yellowish white with three longitudinal orange stripes, with moderately dense white hairs; scutellum yellowish white with white hairs; lateral margin of mesonotum yellowish white; spot next to transverse suture absent (
<figureCitation id="130516E1FF9D4610FC56FAF7FC2DFDB7" box="[931,998,503,528]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,249,1989,2011]" captionTargetBox="[156,1430,768,1958]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,758,1965]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Platypygus americanus holotype: a — lateral view, b — wing, c — dorsal view of mesonotum and abdomen." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248550/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">
Fig. 
<number id="3DF61843FF9D4610FC2FFAF8FC2DFDB7" box="[986,998,504,528]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
c); pleura completely yellowish white without black mark; halter yellowish white; crossvein r-m at middle of cell dm (
<figureCitation id="130516E1FF9D4610FBB4F91BFB48FD93" box="[1089,1155,539,564]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,249,1989,2011]" captionTargetBox="[156,1430,768,1958]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,758,1965]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Platypygus americanus holotype: a — lateral view, b — wing, c — dorsal view of mesonotum and abdomen." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248550/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">
Fig. 
<number id="3DF61843FF9D4610FB8DF91BFB48FD93" box="[1144,1155,539,564]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
b); legs yellowish white except two last tarsal segments blackish; abdomen yellowish with short adpressed whitish hairs dorsally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B810A64FF9D4610FF32F961FEDAFC33" blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1338]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">
<emphasis id="B94AD676FF9D4610FF32F961FE44FDDD" bold="true" box="[199,399,609,634]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">Female genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="130516E1FF9D4610FE57F961FE21FDDD" box="[418,490,609,634]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,249,1923,1945]" captionTargetBox="[239,1323,202,1868]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[227,1335,193,1881]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Platypygus americanus female genitalia. Abbreviations: c = canaliculi, s. r. = spermathecal reservoir, a. s. d. = apical spermathecal duct, b. s. d. = basal spermathecal duct, c. s. d. = common spermathecal duct, f. = furca, s. = sclerite adjacent to genital orifice." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248551/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">
Fig. 
<number id="3DF61843FF9D4610FE2FF962FE21FDDD" box="[474,490,610,634]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
). [Note: Hall &amp; Evenhuis (
<number id="3DF61843FF9D4610FCDFF961FCACFDDD" box="[810,871,609,634]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" value="1986.0">1986</number>
: 
<number id="3DF61843FF9D4610FC80F962FC6BFDDD" box="[885,928,610,634]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" value="328.0">328</number>
) illustrated the female genitalia but did not provide a description. We here give the first description of the female genitalia.] Furca U-shaped, sclerotized, lateral arms thin, birfurcate apically, connected by thickly sclerotized slightly bilobed bridge, with two small linear sclerites next to genital orifice; common spermathecal duct very short; each spermathecal duct divided into two sections, basal section, transversely striated, long, broad, apical section narrow and smooth duct, without distinct sperm pump or valves; basal part of median spermathecal duct narrower than that of lateral ducts, without striation, twisted spirally on basal half, thin, straight on distal half toward reservoir; lateral spermathecal ducts about 
<number id="3DF61843FF9D4610FABFF835FA93FCEA" box="[1354,1368,821,845]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" value="3.0">3</number>
times width of median duct; spermathecal reservoirs obovate, slightly indented medially, with short and dense canaliculi apica 
<number id="3DF61843FF9D4610FF21F87BFF3BFC33" box="[212,240,891,916]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" value="64.0">64</number>
lly.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32459EFFF9D4610FF32F89EFD44FC10" box="[199,655,926,951]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B810A64FF9D4610FF32F89EFD44FC10" blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1338]" box="[199,655,926,951]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">
<emphasis id="B94AD676FF9D4610FF32F89EFE92FC10" bold="true" box="[199,345,926,951]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">Distribution</emphasis>
. 
<collectingCountry id="F3294AF4FF9D4610FE92F89EFE37FC10" box="[359,508,926,951]" name="United States of America" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">United States</collectingCountry>
(California).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32459EFFF9D4610FF32F8C1FE72FA9D" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B810A64FF9D4610FF32F8C1FE72FA9D" blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1338]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">
<emphasis id="B94AD676FF9D4610FF32F8C1FEFFFC7D" bold="true" box="[199,308,961,986]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">Remarks</emphasis>
. Hall &amp; Evenhuis (
<number id="3DF61843FF9D4610FDFBF8C1FD83FC7D" box="[526,584,961,986]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" value="1986.0">1986</number>
) illustrated the adult habitus of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3E71E7FF9D4610FC5BF8C1FAA7FC7D" authority="Melander, 1950" authorityName="Melander" authorityYear="1950" box="[942,1388,961,986]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Platypygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="americanus">
<emphasis id="B94AD676FF9D4610FC5BF8C1FB7EFC7E" box="[942,1205,961,986]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">Platypygus americanus</emphasis>
Melander, 
<number id="3DF61843FF9D4610FAC1F8C1FAA7FC7D" box="[1332,1388,961,986]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" value="1950.0">1950</number>
</taxonomicName>
and its female genitalia and this species was later transferred to 
<taxonomicName id="4C3E71E7FF9D4610FCADF8E5FC15FC5B" box="[856,990,997,1020]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Cyrtisiopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94AD676FF9D4610FCADF8E5FC15FC5B" box="[856,990,997,1020]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">Cyrtisiopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by Evenhuis (
<number id="3DF61843FF9D4610FB7FF8E5FB03FC5A" box="[1162,1224,997,1021]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" value="2002.0">2002</number>
). By checking the 
<typeStatus id="5485B4C6FF9D4610FF62FF07FF32FB87" box="[151,249,1031,1056]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">holotype</typeStatus>
it was clearly revealed that there is no long and acute posterior extension of the postgena (its presence a diagnostic feature of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3E71E7FF9D4610FE7BFF2CFDDFFBE4" box="[398,532,1068,1091]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Cyrtisiopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94AD676FF9D4610FE7BFF2CFDDFFBE4" box="[398,532,1068,1091]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">Cyrtisiopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Also, the female spermathecae of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3E71E7FF9D4610FC49FF2CFB95FBE4" box="[956,1118,1068,1091]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Platypygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="americanus">
<emphasis id="B94AD676FF9D4610FC49FF2CFB95FBE4" box="[956,1118,1068,1091]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">P. americanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="130516E1FF9D4610FB85FF2BFB7CFBE4" box="[1136,1207,1067,1092]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,249,1923,1945]" captionTargetBox="[239,1323,202,1868]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[227,1335,193,1881]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Platypygus americanus female genitalia. Abbreviations: c = canaliculi, s. r. = spermathecal reservoir, a. s. d. = apical spermathecal duct, b. s. d. = basal spermathecal duct, c. s. d. = common spermathecal duct, f. = furca, s. = sclerite adjacent to genital orifice." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/248551/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">
Fig. 
<number id="3DF61843FF9D4610FB5DFF2BFB7CFBE4" box="[1192,1207,1067,1091]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
) contains a spirally twisted median duct that is much narrower than the lateral ducts. This character, as mentioned above, is seen consistently in the spermathecae of the known dissected species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3E71E7FF9D4610FC44FF71FBE6FB2D" box="[945,1069,1137,1162]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Platypygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94AD676FF9D4610FC44FF71FBE6FB2D" box="[945,1069,1137,1162]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">Platypygus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Further, 
<taxonomicName id="4C3E71E7FF9D4610FB51FF72FA8DFB2E" box="[1188,1350,1138,1161]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Platypygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="americanus">
<emphasis id="B94AD676FF9D4610FB51FF72FA8DFB2E" box="[1188,1350,1138,1161]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">P. americanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has an uncurved reservoir similar to species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3E71E7FF9D4610FD99FF94FD23FB0A" box="[620,744,1172,1197]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Platypygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94AD676FF9D4610FD99FF94FD23FB0A" box="[620,744,1172,1197]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">Platypygus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
while a curved spermathecal reservoir is seen in the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C3E71E7FF9D4610FF62FFB8FED6FB68" box="[151,285,1208,1231]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Cyrtisiopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94AD676FF9D4610FF62FFB8FED6FB68" box="[151,285,1208,1231]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">Cyrtisiopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Also in the wing of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3E71E7FF9D4610FDFCFFB9FD6CFB77" box="[521,679,1209,1232]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Platypygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="americanus">
<emphasis id="B94AD676FF9D4610FDFCFFB9FD6CFB77" box="[521,679,1209,1232]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">P. americanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, cell br is longer than bm cell, while species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3E71E7FF9D4610FB49FFB8FA89FB68" box="[1212,1346,1208,1231]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Cyrtisiopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94AD676FF9D4610FB49FFB8FA89FB68" box="[1212,1346,1208,1231]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">Cyrtisiopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have br cell equal in length to bm cell. As a result, we feel 
<taxonomicName id="4C3E71E7FF9D4610FD2DFFDCFCBDFB54" box="[728,886,1244,1267]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Platypygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="americanus">
<emphasis id="B94AD676FF9D4610FD2DFFDCFCBDFB54" box="[728,886,1244,1267]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">P. americanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was correctly described in the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C3E71E7FF9D4610FAEAFFDBFA50FB53" box="[1311,1435,1243,1268]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Platypygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94AD676FF9D4610FAEAFFDBFA50FB53" box="[1311,1435,1243,1268]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">Platypygus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by Melander (
<number id="3DF61843FF9D4610FEC0FFFEFEA4FAB0" box="[309,367,1278,1303]" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" value="1950.0">1950</number>
) and here we return it to its original combination as 
<taxonomicName id="4C3E71E7FF9D4610FC36FFFEFB01FAB1" box="[963,1226,1278,1303]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Platypygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="205" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="americanus">
<emphasis id="B94AD676FF9D4610FC36FFFEFB01FAB1" box="[963,1226,1278,1303]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="205">Platypygus americanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The males of this species are still unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
